# Vue Vben Admin - Cursor IDE Rules

You are an expert Vue 3 + TypeScript + Vite developer working on Vue Vben Admin, an enterprise-level admin template. Follow these rules strictly.

## Project Architecture

### Monorepo Structure
- This is a pnpm workspace monorepo with multiple apps and packages
- Main apps: `web-antd`, `web-ele`, `web-naive`, `backend-mock`, `playground`
- Shared packages in `packages/` directory
- Use workspace references (`workspace:*`) for internal dependencies

### Technology Stack
- **Frontend**: Vue 3 Composition API, TypeScript, Vite 6, Ant Design Vue
- **State Management**: Pinia
- **Routing**: Vue Router 4  
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS, SCSS
- **Testing**: Vitest, Playwright
- **Backend Mock**: Nitro framework
- **Build**: Vite with custom configurations

## Code Style & Standards

### TypeScript
- Use strict TypeScript configuration
- Always define interfaces for props, emit events, and data structures
- Use `ref()`, `reactive()`, `computed()` from Vue
- Prefer `const` over `let`, avoid `var`
- Use proper type annotations, avoid `any`

```typescript
// ✅ Good
interface UserItem {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  status: 'active' | 'inactive';
}

const users = ref<UserItem[]>([]);

// ❌ Bad  
const users = ref([]);
```

### Vue Components
- Use `<script setup lang="ts">` syntax
- Use Composition API exclusively
- Define component props with TypeScript interfaces
- Use proper component naming (PascalCase)

```vue
<!-- ✅ Good -->
<script setup lang="ts">
interface Props {
  title: string;
  items: UserItem[];
}

const props = defineProps<Props>();
const emit = defineEmits<{
  update: [value: string];
}>();
</script>

<!-- ❌ Bad -->
<script setup>
const props = defineProps(['title', 'items']);
</script>
```

### File Structure
- Components: PascalCase (`UserList.vue`)
- Composables: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useUserManagement.ts`)
- Utils: camelCase (`formatDate.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase interfaces/types (`types.ts`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

### Import Rules
- Use path aliases: `#/` for src files, `@vben/` for packages
- Group imports: Vue/3rd party → Internal packages → Local files
- Use explicit imports, avoid default exports for utilities

```typescript
// ✅ Good
import { computed, ref } from 'vue';
import { Button, Table } from 'ant-design-vue';
import { Page } from '@vben/common-ui';
import type { UserItem } from '#/types/user';

// ❌ Bad
import * as Vue from 'vue';
import AntD from 'ant-design-vue';
```

## Vue Vben Admin Specific

### Component Structure
- Use `@vben/common-ui` components (Page, Card, etc.)
- Follow existing layout patterns
- Use Ant Design Vue components consistently
- Implement proper loading states and error handling

### Routing
- Define routes in `src/router/routes/modules/`
- Use proper meta configuration for permissions, titles
- Follow existing route structure patterns

```typescript
// ✅ Good
const routes: RouteRecordRaw[] = [
  {
    meta: {
      icon: 'ic:baseline-people',
      keepAlive: true,
      order: 200,
      title: '用户管理',
    },
    name: 'UserManagement',
    path: '/user-management',
    children: [...],
  },
];
```

### State Management
- Use Pinia stores for complex state
- Keep component state local when possible
- Use composables for reusable logic

### API Integration
- Define API functions in `src/api/` directory
- Use proper TypeScript interfaces for requests/responses
- Handle loading states and error cases
- Use consistent error handling patterns

## Styling Guidelines

### Tailwind CSS
- Use Tailwind classes for styling
- Follow responsive design patterns
- Use consistent spacing scale
- Prefer Tailwind over custom CSS

```vue
<!-- ✅ Good -->
<div class="flex flex-col gap-4 p-6">
  <Card class="mb-4">
    <div class="flex justify-between items-center">

<!-- ❌ Bad -->
<div style="display: flex; gap: 16px;">
```

### Component Styling
- Use scoped styles when custom CSS is needed
- Follow BEM methodology for custom classes
- Maintain consistency with design system

## Development Patterns

### Error Handling
- Always handle async operations properly
- Use try/catch for API calls
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Implement loading states

```typescript
// ✅ Good
const loading = ref(false);

const fetchUsers = async () => {
  try {
    loading.value = true;
    const data = await userApi.getUsers();
    users.value = data;
  } catch (error) {
    message.error('Failed to load users');
    console.error('Error fetching users:', error);
  } finally {
    loading.value = false;
  }
};
```

### Performance
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Implement proper list keys
- Use `v-memo` for expensive renders when needed
- Lazy load routes and components

### Testing
- Write unit tests for utilities and composables
- Test component behavior, not implementation
- Use meaningful test descriptions
- Mock external dependencies

## Specific Rules

### Forms & Validation
- Use Ant Design Vue form components
- Implement proper validation with clear error messages
- Handle form submission states

### Tables & Data Display
- Use Ant Design Vue Table component
- Implement pagination, sorting, filtering
- Handle empty states properly
- Use proper column configurations

### Internationalization
- Use the built-in i18n system
- Define translations in appropriate locale files
- Use translation keys consistently

### Security
- Sanitize user inputs
- Use proper authentication checks
- Follow OWASP guidelines
- Never expose sensitive data in frontend

## File Naming Conventions

### Components
- `index.vue` for main component in folder
- `components/` subfolder for related components
- Use descriptive, specific names

### API Files
- Group by feature: `user/`, `auth/`, etc.
- Use descriptive function names: `getUserList`, `updateUser`

### Types
- `types.ts` for component-specific types
- `index.ts` for package exports
- Use descriptive interface names

## Code Review Guidelines

### Before Committing
- Ensure TypeScript compilation passes
- Run linting and fix all issues
- Test functionality thoroughly
- Update documentation if needed

### Code Quality
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use descriptive variable names
- Add comments for complex logic
- Remove console.logs before committing

### Git Practices
- Use conventional commit messages
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Write clear pull request descriptions

## Performance Optimization

### Bundle Size
- Use dynamic imports for routes
- Tree-shake unused code
- Optimize images and assets
- Monitor bundle analysis

### Runtime Performance
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Use proper Vue reactivity patterns
- Implement virtual scrolling for large lists
- Optimize API calls

## Debugging Guidelines

### Development
- Use Vue DevTools for component debugging
- Use browser DevTools for performance analysis
- Log meaningful information for debugging
- Handle edge cases gracefully

## Documentation

### Code Documentation
- Document complex functions and components
- Use JSDoc comments for public APIs
- Keep README files updated
- Document setup and deployment procedures

### Comments
- Explain why, not what
- Keep comments up to date
- Use TODO comments for future improvements
- Document workarounds and their reasons

Remember: This is an enterprise-level project. Prioritize maintainability, performance, and developer experience. Always consider the impact of changes on the entire monorepo structure. 
